description: ISS043E122274 (04/17/2015) --- ESA (European Space Agency) astronaut Samantha Cristoforetti seen here in the Cupola, a special module that provides a 360-degree view of the International Space Station. The Cupola houses robotics work station controls and is used to monitor spacewalks and docking operations.

ISS022-E-069162 (19 Feb. 2010) --- The space shuttle Endeavour is featured in this image photographed by an Expedition 22 crew member from a window in the Cupola of the International Space Station. Endeavour, docked to the station, was photographed during the STS-130 mission's first spacewalk.

ISS022-E-069156 (19 Feb. 2010) --- The space shuttle Endeavour is featured in this image photographed by an Expedition 22 crew member from a window in the Cupola of the International Space Station. Endeavour, docked to the station, was photographed during the STS-130 mission's first spacewalk.

ISS031-E-089012 (5 June 2012) --- Transit of Venus across the sun observed from the International Space Station. This rare astronomical event was photographed by Expedition 31 crew members from the Cupola module.

ISS022-E-069146 (19 Feb. 2010) --- The space shuttle Endeavour is featured in this image photographed by an Expedition 22 crew member from a window in the Cupola of the International Space Station. Endeavour, docked to the station, was photographed during the STS-130 mission's first spacewalk.

JOHNSON SPACE CENTER, Houston - STS130-S-001 - The STS130 patch was designed by the crew to reflect both the objective of the mission and the pride the crew feels in being part of the continuing construction of the International Space Station.

STS130-S-001 (September 2009) --- The STS130 patch was designed by the crew to reflect both the objective of the mission and the pride the crew feels in being part of the continuing construction of the International Space Station.

ISS040-E-068644 (16 July 2014) --- The Orbital Sciences' Cygnus cargo craft (bottom center) is photographed by an Expedition 40 crew member from a window in the Cupola of the International Space Station. The Canadarm2 robotic arm is visible in the foreground.

ISS040-E-006183 (1 June 2014) --- The Permanent Multipurpose Module (PMM), the Soyuz 39 (TMA-13M) spacecraft and the Progress 55 (55P) cargo craft are visible in this image photographed by an Expedition 40 crew member from a window in the Cupola of the International Space Station.

ISS038-E-015274 (12 Dec. 2013) --- The Permanent Multipurpose Module (PMM) and the Soyuz 37 (TMA-11M) spacecraft are visible in this image photographed by an Expedition 38 crew member from a window in the Cupola of the International Space Station.

ISS040-E-006230 (30 May 2014) --- Two Russian spacecraft docked to the International Space Station are visible in this image photographed by an Expedition 40 crew member from a window in the Cupola of the International Space Station.

ISS040-E-005999 (29 May 2014) --- Two Russian spacecraft docked to the International Space Station are visible in this image photographed by an Expedition 40 crew member from a window in the Cupola of the International Space Station.

ISS040-E-068656 (16 July 2014) --- The Orbital Sciences' Cygnus cargo craft (bottom center) is photographed by an Expedition 40 crew member from a window in the Cupola of the International Space Station. The Canadarm2 robotic arm is visible in the foreground.

ISS034-E-062471 (3 March 2013) --- This is one of a series of photos taken by the Expedition 34 crew from the Cupola of the International Space Station showing the Canadarm2 robotic arm during operations.

ISS022-E-066963 (17 Feb. 2010) --- This image is among the first taken through a first of its kind 'bay window' on the International Space Station, the seven-windowed Cupola. The image shows the coast of Algeria featuring (in the Cupola's round window) an area between the cities of Dellys and Algiers.

ISS040-E-123163 (2 Sept. 2014) --- Various solar array panels, the Rassvet Mini-Research Module 1 (MRM-1) and the Soyuz 40 (TMA-14M) spacecraft are visible in this image photographed by an Expedition 40 crew member from a window in the Cupola of the International Space Station.

ISS040-E-123166 (2 Sept. 2014) --- Various solar array panels, the Rassvet Mini-Research Module 1 (MRM-1) and the Soyuz 40 (TMA-14M) spacecraft are visible in this image photographed by an Expedition 40 crew member from a window in the Cupola of the International Space Station.

ISS040-E-046846 (6 July 2014) --- One of the Expedition 40 crew members aboard the Earth-orbiting International Space Station photographed this image of Earth's horizon and the blackness of space from a window in the Cupola.

ISS040-E-047616 (6 July 2014) --- One of the Expedition 40 crew members aboard the Earth-orbiting International Space Station photographed this image of Earth's horizon and the blackness of space from a window in the Cupola.

ISS022-E-068277 (18 Feb. 2010) --- An orbital sunrise is featured in this image photographed by Japanese astronaut Soichi Noguchi, Expedition 22 flight engineer, from a window in the Cupola of the International Space Station.

ISS040-E-047594 (6 July 2014) --- One of the Expedition 40 crew members aboard the Earth-orbiting International Space Station photographed this image of Earth's horizon and the blackness of space from a window in the Cupola.
ISS040-E-006000 (29 May 2014) --- One of the six Expedition 40 crew members positioned himself in the Cupola to photograph this image of Earth's horizon and the blackness of space.

S130-E-009694 (17 Feb. 2010) --- This image is among the initial series taken through a first of its kind 'bay window' on the International Space Station, the seven-windowed Cupola. The image shows the coast of Algeria featuring (in the Cupola's round window) an area between the cities of Dellys and Algiers.
ISS038-E-042112 (6 Feb. 2014) --- A fresh apple floating freely near a window in the Cupola of the International Space Station is featured in this image photographed by an Expedition 38 crew member.

ISS026-E-031247 (2 March 2011) --- Backdropped by Earth's horizon and the blackness of space, the Cupola is pictured in this image photographed by an Expedition 26 crew member from a window in the International Space Station.

ISS042E340851 (03/09/2015) --- Crewmembers on the International Space Station are treated to Earth views that are constantly changing. NASA Astronaut Terry Virts Commander of Expedition 43, ESA (European Space Agency) astronaut Samantha Cristoforetti and Russian cosmonaut Mikhail Kornienko both flight engineers enjoy the wonder of Earths changing vista's from the stations cupola, a series of special windows that allow 360 degree views.

CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. -- This is a printable version of space shuttle Endeavour's orbiter tribute, or OV-105, which hangs in Firing Room 4 of the Launch Control Center at NASA's Kennedy Space Center in Florida. The tribute includes the STS-130 mission patch and highlights the Cupola module delivery.

ISS042E033478 (12/09/2014) --- ESA (European Space Agency) astronaut Samantha Cristoforetti took this photograph of the aurora from the Cupola of the International Space Station during Expedition 42.
ISS028-E-005527 (25 May 2011) --- The International Space Station's Tranquility node and Cupola are featured in this image photographed by an Expedition 28 crew member from a window in the station.
